  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">DRC COVID-19 Global Appeal Americas Region</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">DRC is present in &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.drc.ngo/where-we-work/colombia&quot;&gt;Colombia&lt;/a&gt; in the Americas Region and have implemented Covid-19 specific activities here.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">DRC&#x2019;s response in Latin America and the Caribbean covered Colombia, Mexico and Peru.  Since the beginning of the pandemic, DRC focused on protection monitoring which has allowed for the identification of major needs such as food and shelter assistance &#x2013; such as payment of rent - as well as identifying persons with specific needs and offer them focused protection services (Individual Protection Assistance, IPA). In the second part of 2020, DRC expanded its outreach in the region.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">&lt;b&gt; Colombia&lt;/b&gt; hosts approximately 2,000,000 refugees and migrants from Venezuela. 80% of them are irregular migrants with humanitarian needs and vulnerable to COVID-19 primary and secondary effects. Throughout 2020, in &lt;b&gt; Colombia and Mexico&lt;/b&gt; multi-purpose cash assistance was used as the optimal modality to cater for their immediate needs and to reduce the burden of the worsening humanitarian situation. In &lt;b&gt; Peru &lt;/b&gt;, beneficiaries of multipurpose cash were single parent families, women at risk, and families at risk of eviction for being late in paying their rent. Surveys show that the support was used to pay rent and buy food. 

&lt;br&gt; &lt;br&gt;Targets for the Global Appeal for the region have been reached and exceeded in the sectors of: &lt;b&gt; Protection, Basic Needs and Camp Management and Shelter/Settlements&lt;b/&gt;.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">&lt;br&gt; &lt;br&gt; &lt;b&gt; The OECD DAC CRS Purpose Codes &lt;/b&gt; used to describe this activity refers to the amount of people reached, seen as a percentage of all single instances of beneficiaries reached. This means that it can include double counting, if single individuals have been counted multiple times for different sectors.</narrative>
  </description>
